-- PJM Western Hub Power Advances as Hot Weather Boosts Demand
-- B y   C h r i s t i n e   B u u r m a
-- 2013-04-08T19:48:10Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-04-08/pjm-western-hub-power-advances-as-hot-weather-boosts-demand.html
Wholesale electricity on the eastern
U.S. grid operated by PJM Interconnection LLC gained for the
fifth time in six days on forecasts of above-normal temperatures
that would boost demand.  Spot prices covering on-peak hours increased 23 percent.
The operator of the 13-state grid stretching from  New Jersey 
into North Carolina and Illinois boosted its forecast for demand
today. Temperatures will be above-normal on the East Coast
through April 12, according to Commodity Weather Group LLC in
Bethesda,  Maryland .  Electricity at PJM’s benchmark Western Hub, which includes
prices from Pennsylvania to Washington, rose $7.5886 to $40.8667
a megawatt-hour at 2 p.m. from the April 5 on-peak average,
according to the grid operator. On-peak hours run from 7 a.m. to
11 p.m.  The high today in Washington may be 79 degrees Fahrenheit
(26 Celsius), 15 above normal, compared with yesterday’s high of
71 degrees, 7 more than average, according to  AccuWeather Inc. 
in  State College , Pennsylvania.  PJM predicted peak  power usage  of 88,043 megawatts at 8:30
p.m., compared with yesterday’s estimate of 87,470 for that
time.  Spot power gained in  New York  and New England.  New York City prices fell $4.0335, or 7.6 percent, to
$49.0071 a megawatt-hour from yesterday’s on-peak average,
according to the  New York Independent System Operator Inc.   On-peak prices  on the six-state grid from Connecticut to
 Maine  slid $9.8533, or 21 percent, to $37.038 a megawatt-hour
from the previous day’s average, ISO New England Inc. data
showed.  To contact the reporter on this story:
